oakcurric:unit-3674
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Collaborative design: tactile toys to teach"@en ;
  curric:slug "collaborative-design-tactile-toys-to-teach" ;
  rdfs:comment """Using knowledge of timber properties and processes, pupils will work together to
  design a batch of tactile toys. They will prepare a manufacturing plan and develop their
  knowledge of quality control, applying this to checks throughout manufacturing to produce
  the batch within acceptable tolerances."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils need to develop and apply knowledge of industrial manufacturing
  processes and understand their limitations. This unit introduces scales of production with a
  focus on batch production and collaborative design. This unit builds upon the knowledge and
  understanding of manufacturing processes learnt in the previous unit in Year 7, 'Materials
  and manufacturing', and the Year 6 unit, 'Cams: automata', during which pupils developed
  their knowledge and skills for ensuring accuracy when manufacturing. This unit prepares
  pupils for the technical principles unit in Key Stage 4.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3674-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3674-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3674-3 ;
  curric:id "3674"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.167124Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oakcurric:thread-materials ,
    oakcurric:thread-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-critique-and-evaluate ,
    oakcurric:thread-manufacture .

oakcurric:unit-3676
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Material testing"@en ;
  curric:slug "material-testing" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will develop pupils' knowledge of the physical and working properties of
  materials. They will compare material properties through testing, with a focus on metals.
  The environmental and social impact of materials will also be introduced."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Material selection and justification are key to successful design
  development. This unit builds on the Year 7 unit, 'Principles of materials and
  manufacturing,' where pupils learnt how to group materials and manufacturing processes. This
  unit will develop pupils' confidence when articulating design decisions independently in the
  subsequent iterative design units in Year 10, 'Iterative design: Nature' and 'Interative
  design: Student Living'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3676-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3676-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3676-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3676-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3676-5 ;
  curric:id "3676"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.269369Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-materials ,
    oakcurric:thread-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-critique-and-evaluate ,
    oakcurric:thread-manufacture .

oakcurric:unit-3672
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Prototypes with mechanisms: robotics and automation"@en ;
  curric:slug "prototypes-with-mechanisms-promotional-displays" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils will model with paper and boards and learn about sources and stock forms.
  They will develop 3D computer-aided design knowledge and skills, applying this by
  designing and simulating mechanical systems using TinkerCAD."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Modelling in card and computer aided design are fundamental techniques
  that enable pupils to communicate and test ideas effectively. Pupils will develop these
  techniques, building on the knowledge and skills learnt previously in the Year 6 unit 'Cams:
  automata'. They will also develop their knowledge and understanding of more complex
  mechanisms to create different types of movement. Pupils will learn how to model and use
  simulations to test designs in computer aided design, leading to greater independence in the
  Year 10 unit 'Systems approach to design: sustainable Futures'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3672-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3672-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3672-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3672-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3672-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3672-6 ;
  curric:id "3672"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.359937Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-user-centred-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-systems ,
    oakcurric:thread-materials ,
    oakcurric:thread-design .

oakcurric:unit-3671
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Principles of materials and manufacturing"@en ;
  curric:slug "principles-of-materials-and-manufacturing" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils will handle, shape and join sheet materials using different manufacturing
  processes. They will test and experiment with different mechanical fixing methods and
  adhesives and then use this knowledge to explain which choices are suitable and why."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Knowledge of how to identify different materials and their properties
  alongside different manufacturing processes is fundamental for pupils to design and make with
  increasing independence. This unit builds on pupils' knowledge of materials from the Year 6
  unit, 'People and places'. This unit also builds on the manufacturing processes of cutting
  and shaping timber materials in the Year 6 unit, 'Cams: automata'. This lays the foundations
  for pupils to manufacture safely and accurately in the Year 8 unit, 'Collaborative design:
  tactile toys to teach'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3671-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3671-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3671-3 ;
  curric:id "3671"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.066899Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-materials ,
    oakcurric:thread-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-manufacture .

oakcurric:unit-3680
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Functional prototypes: wearable technology"@en ;
  curric:slug "functional-prototypes-wearable-technology" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils will deepen their understanding of systems and control. They will be
  introduced to engineered fabrics and the associated manufacturing processes. This
  knowledge and understanding will be applied through the design and manufacture of a
  wearable technology product."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Integrating control systems into fabric products gives pupils the
  opportunity to work across material areas. This unit builds on the knowledge from the Year 6
  unit 'Systems and control: sensor alarm', where pupils used a microcontroller. Pupils will
  deepen their understanding of textiles and their manufacturing processes, building on the
  Year 5 unit 'Combining fabrics: accessible textiles'. This unit increases pupils'
  independence which will prepare them for the year 10 unit, 'Systems approach to design:
  Sustainable Futures' and the Non-Examined Assessment.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3680-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3680-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3680-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3680-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3680-5 ;
  curric:id "3680"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.132291Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-systems ,
    oakcurric:thread-materials ,
    oakcurric:thread-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-critique-and-evaluate ,
    oakcurric:thread-manufacture .

oakcurric:unit-3675
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Ergonomic design: accessible controllers"@en ;
  curric:slug "ergonomic-design-accessible-controllers" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils will gather and analyse ergonomic and anthropometric data to inform the
  design of a game controller. Pupils will be introduced to polymer properties and
  processes. They will develop and apply foam and complex card modelling techniques to
  manufacture their product."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """To create effective designs, pupils must understand the users' needs. This
  involves empathising and gathering user feedback throughout iterative designing. This unit
  builds on the inclusive design knowledge in the Year 5 unit 'Combining fabrics: accessible
  textiles'. This unit will enable pupils to design with greater empathy in the Year 10 unit
  'Inclusive design: An ageing population' and during the Non-Examined Assessment.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3675-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3675-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3675-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3675-4 ;
  curric:id "3675"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.333588Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-user-centred-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-materials ,
    oakcurric:thread-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-critique-and-evaluate ,
    oakcurric:thread-manufacture .

oakcurric:unit-3673
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Communication"@en ;
  curric:slug "communication" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils will develop knowledge and skills of communication, including freehand 3D
  sketching using the crating technique. They will learn how to render to show texture and
  tone. They will also learn how to draw using more formal techniques, such as one-point
  perspective and orthographic projection."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Proficient drawing skills enable pupils to communicate increasingly
  complex designs confidently. This unit focuses on developing knowledge and skills in drawing
  techniques to communicate designs in various ways. It builds upon the previous unit in Year
  6, 'Cams,' where pupils learn about cross-sectional diagrams. Knowledge within this unit
  progresses so pupils confidently communicate designs using suitable strategies in the Year 8
  unit, 'Controllers,' and Year 10, 'Student living.'""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3673-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3673-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3673-3 ;
  curric:id "3673"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.710508Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-design .

oakcurric:unit-3679
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Circular economy"@en ;
  curric:slug "circular-economy" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will develop knowledge of technology in society and its
  effects on design. Through the life cycle assessment of popular products, they will learn
  how to be responsible designers."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding the circular economy and being able to assess the life cycle
  of a product is key to becoming a responsible designer. Pupils will learn about the
  environmental, social and moral issues of designing products through a smartphone case study.
  This environmental knowledge builds on the learning in the Year 8 'Materials testing' unit
  and the Year 7 'Principles of materials and manufacturing' unit. This unit prepares students
  to apply responsible design principles to the Year 10 units 'Iterative design: Nature' and
  'Interative design: Student Living'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3679-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3679-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3679-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3679-4 ;
  curric:id "3679"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.721739Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oakcurric:thread-materials ,
    oakcurric:thread-critique-and-evaluate .

oakcurric:unit-3678
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Developments in new materials: supporting new parents"@en ;
  curric:slug "developments-in-new-materials-supporting-new-parents" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils will develop knowledge of smart and modern materials and
  apply this to designing a product to support new parents. They will develop strategies for
  generating ideas by investigating a specific context."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will develop their design thinking to consider an increasingly
  complex range of problems. This unit focuses on user centred design and materials knowledge
  and understanding. Building on the Year 8 unit 'Materials testing, ' pupils will learn about
  smart and modern materials and how these can be incorporated into a product. Pupils will
  develop their research knowledge from the Year 8 'Ergonomic design: accessible controllers'
  unit. This unit leads to interative design units such as the Year 10 'Product analysis:
  Encouraging healthy lifestyles' unit and the Non-Examined Assessment.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3678-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3678-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3678-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3678-4 ;
  curric:id "3678"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.723693Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
